<HEAD>Eye of the Storm: Calm at Shrine Claimed By Hindus and Moslems</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with death reported in Lucknow,
Hindu fundamentalists say thousands of followers are hiding near
disputed site. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ```Communal tension..'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIJAY JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AYODHYA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bored policemen shoo monkeys and glance
sleepily at closed-circuit television cameras as they enforce a
curfew in this town whose name has become a battle cry in India's
latest political and religious crisis.
   About 100 people have been killed throughout India in the past
week in riots caused by Hindu plans to build a temple on a dusty
hilltop where a Moslem mosque now stands.
   The latest death was reported today in Lucknow, capital of Uttar
Pradesh state 75 miles west of Ayodhya. Police officials said Hindu
crowds surged through a Moslem neighborhood throwing bricks.
   The religious feud has precipitated a political crisis that has
brought Prime Minister V.P. Singh's government to the brink of
collapse.
   But the firestorm raging elsewhere in the country is masked by
inactivity and tight security in Ayodhya, where Hindu
fundamentalists vow they will get through roadblocks and start
building their temple to the god Rama on Tuesday.
   The fundamentalists said today in a handwritten communique that
thousands of followers were hiding near Ayodhya and were ready to
start building.
   ``Communal tension will flare up all over the country, but an
Ayodhya resident will not let a drop of blood be spilled because
then Rama's name will be sullied,'' said Mudit Sharma, who works
for a Hindu charity near the disputed site.
   ``Moslems of the area are not any diferent from Hindus,''
Sharma said. ``They participate in our festivals. We go to their
house during Islamic festivals. All these fights are because of
political loafers.''
   The fundamentalist cause has been espoused by the Hindu
right-wing Bharatiya Janata Party. Its top leaders are among the
more about 80,000 people arrested in the last week while trying to
march to Ayodhya, 300 miles east of New Delhi.
   The arrests prompted the party to withdraw its support for
Singh's coalition government, leaving him without the parliamentary
majority needed to stay in office.
   Singh, who plans to face Parliament for a vote of confidence on
Nov. 7, wants the temple-mosque dispute settled in court.
   The fundamentalists claim the mosque stands atop the very spot
where Lord Rama was born and therefore is a religious matter, not a
legal one. Moslems, a minority in officially secular but
predominantly Hindu India, fear the displacement of one mosque
could jeopardize hundreds of other Islamic sites across the
country.
   The mosque, called the Babri Masjid, was constructed in the 16th
century when Mogul armies conquered northern India. Hindu
fundamentalists claimed the Moslem conquerors destroyed a Rama
temple on the spot where the mosque now stands.
   The Hindu World Council, backed by the Bharatiya Janata Party,
has organized the campaign to build the temple by either moving or
demolishing the little mosque.
   On Friday, the government of Uttar Pradesh state imposed an
around-the-clock curfew in Ayodhya to keep temple advocates from
reaching the disputed hilltop. Trains to the area were halted and
roads blocked by police and paramilitary troops.
   ``They have made Ayodhya into a cantonment for political gains.
Let them arrest us, but thousands of devotees will come to Ayodhya
tomorrow,'' said Tara Kant Jha, secretary of the World Hindu
Council's local office in Ayodhya.
   The council and the Bharatiya Janata Party claim the
government's tough stand on Ayodhya is only a bid to win Moslem
votes.
   Moslems make up 12 percent of India's 880 million people, of
whom 82 percent are Hindu. In Uttar Pradesh state, where the
government is allied with Singh, Moslems account for about 30
percent of the 120 million people.
   Hindu-Moslem clashes occur periodically in other parts of Uttar
Pradesh, but no one can remember trouble around Ayodhya or its twin
town of Faizabad, three miles down the road. About a quarter of the
area's population is Moslem.
   ``There never has been any communal tension in Faizabad or
Ayodhya. And I don't think there will be after Oct. 30,'' the date
deemed auspicious by Hindu astrologers to start building the Rama
temple, said District Commissioner Madhukar Gupta, the top civil
administrator of the area.
   Most residents agree. They seem unconcerned about the curfew,
but business is suffering.
   Ayodhya is a major Hindu pilgrimage site. There are about 6,000
temples in the town of 45,000 people on the banks of the River
Saryu.
   Most people live on the business generated by tens of thousands
of Hindu pilgrims who arrive every year in October for a Hindu
festival.
   About 20,000 security troops deployed around Ayodhya have
prevented pilgrims from entering Ayodhya this week, fearing Hindu
activists may infiltrate the town.
   Elaborate security arrangements include closed-circuit
television cameras and iron gates every 20 yards on the lane
leading to the disputed hilltop.
</TEXT>
