<HEAD>Defection Of Hindu Fundamentalist Party Threatens Singh Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A right-wing Hindu party withdrew its
support for Prime Minister V.P. Singh's government today,
threatening to bring down the fragile coalition that has governed
India for the past 10 months.
   Singh refused to resign and said he would take the battle to
floor of Parliament, where his centrist National Front government
had relied on the votes of the Hindu fundamentalist Bharatiya
Janata Party to survive.
   The crisis was precipitated by the arrest earlier Tuesday of
Bharatiya Janata's president, Lal Krishna Advani, as he led a
cross-country march to muster support for building a new Hindu
temple on the site of a 16th century Moslem mosque.
   About six hours later, party leaders submitted a letter to
Indian President Ramaswamy Venkataraman withdrawing support for
Singh's National Front government.
   The prime minister told reporters at the presidential palace
that the loss of Bharatiya Janata support ``doesn't mean that all
support is gone.'' However, it was unclear how he could avoid
calling new elections.
   With the defection of the Bharatiya Janata Party, Singh's
centrist government loses the fragile majority it cobbled together
from across the political spectrum after November general
elections.
   No single party had won enough seats to take power unilaterally.
   The next steps are up to Singh and the president.
   Under the constitution, the options include Singh's resignation
as prime minister and elections for a new Parliament.
   President Venkataraman could also ask Singh to try to muster a
new majority in Parliament, which appears mathematically and
politically improbable.
   Or, the president can turn to the opposition leader, former
Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, and ask if Gandhi's Congress Party
could form a coalition government.
   That also appears unlikely.
   The crisis was precipitated by Advani's determination to go
ahead with his march to bolster support for the campaign to replace
a Moslem mosque with a temple to the Hindu god Lord Rama.
   Singh had urged Hindu fundamentalists to postpone the temple
plan. At least 80 people died this month in Hindu-Moslem clashes
spurred by the dispute.
   In a nationally televised address Monday night, Singh renewed
his appeal and said he was prepared to face the fact that his stand
could bring down the government.
   ``Religious fanaticism is the first step towards the foundation
for a theocratic state,'' Singh said in his 20-minute TV speech.
``It will be the death of India as a secular state.''
   The prime minister added: ``Hundreds of governments can come and
go, but the nation should remain one.''
   Advani was arrested about sunrise in a remote part of Bihar
state near the village of Samastipur, about 450 miles southeast of
New Delhi.
   He had been leading a caravan of supporters across the Hindu
heartland to demonstrate and bolster support for plans to build a
temple on a site now occupied by a 16th century mosque in the holy
Hindu town of Ayodhya. Ayodhya is in Uttar Pradesh state, which
lies between New Delhi and Bihar state.
   Advani's planned path through Bihar and Uttar Pradesh en route
to Ayodhya would have taken him through poor villages populated by
both Moslems and Hindus. In Bihar especially, these villages have
been recurring flashpoints for Hindu-Moslem violence.
   Hindu fundamentalists have vowed to start building the temple in
one week on the spot where they say the Hindu god Lord Rama was
born. Moslem activists and religious leaders have vowed to prevent
any encroachment on the mosque.
   The outcry has torn at the social and political fabric of
officially secular India, where 82 percent of the 880 million
people are Hindus. Moslems form 12 percent of the population.
   Singh took office in December after ousting Gandhi and his
Congress Party in the November general election. Although the
Congress Party and its allies hold 210 of Parliament's 522 seats,
it lacked the majority to govern.
   Singh's National Front coalition holds just 141 seats, but it
won the tacit support of the two extremes of India's political
spectrum: Advani's right-wing Hindu party and the Left Front
alliance of several communist parties.
   With that support, Singh could draw on enough votes to give him
the majority needed to pass legislation and stay in power.
   Bharatiya Janata has 88 members of Parliament, the Left Front
51.
</TEXT>
