<BYLINE>By VIJAY JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AYODHYA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops opened fire today on Hindu
fundamentalists who broke through police lines and surged toward a
holy site claimed by both Hindus and Moslems. At least five people
were killed and 20 wounded.
   Thirteen more people died in Hindu-Moslem clashes in several
cities hundreds of miles away, police said. At least 125 people
have been killed in riots across India this past week, most in
clashes between Hindus and Moslems.
   The dispute threatens to topple the government of Prime Minister
V.P. Singh, who opposes the Hindu campaign to replace a
16th-century Moslem mosque.
   Militant members of the country's Hindu majority had said they
would begin tearing down the mosque today and replacing it with a
temple.
   Singh today repeated his offer to resign if members of his party
in Parliament ``feel that change of leadership will serve larger
goals.'' He made a similar offer Monday.
   About 200 Hindus eventually reached the site today in Ayodhya.
Those who got through planted Hindu religious flags on the mosque
in victory before police drove them away.
   About 10,000 people who had surged past police barricades
surrounded the perimeter of the disputed site when three Hindu holy
men urged them to halt the violence, saying they had negotiated a
peaceful sttlement with local officials. But part of the crowd
apparently did not hear the appeal and pushed toward the mosque,
setting fire to six police jeeps along the way.
   Police then opened fire. The federal government later announced
that five people were killed. About 20 others were injured by the
gunfire, witnesses said.
   Hindu holy men screamed obscenities from rooftops and pelted the
police with stones. At least four officers were injured.
   Many of the militant Hindus were beaten back by police, who
fired tear gas and lashed out with iron-tipped bamboo canes. Dozens
were injured.
   The crowd initially halted about 100 yards from the mosque,
where police and paramilitary troops stood with rifles ready. But
later about 200 Hindus broke through police lines and reached the
small, one-story mosque.
   Young men wearing orange headbands, the color of the Hindu
faith, climbed atop the mosque and chipped concrete from each of
its three domes, claiming this was a ``symbolic destruction'' of
the Islamic shrine.
   They planted a saffron flag atop each dome before police drove
them away. Jubilant crowds poured through the streets, shouting
``Victory to mother India!''
   In New Delhi, the government's chief spokesman, Ramamohan Rao,
said there was no damage to the mosque.
   The World Hindu Council, which is leading the temple program,
said it would go ahead with its construction effort.
   ``We will only rest when the temple in complete,'' Girilal
Kishore, a Hindu holy man and senior official of the council told
reporters in New Delhi.
   Ayodha, a city of 40,000 people, had been under a
round-the-clock curfew since Friday and roads leading to the mosque
were blocked as authorities tried to halt any attempt to tear down
the mosque.
   But people emerged from hiding places in fields around Ayodhya
before sunrise and stormed a bridge leading into the town.
   About 20,000 police and paramilitary troops were deployed in and
around Ayodhya, 300 miles southeast of New Delhi. They were among
200,000 security troops on alert throughout Uttar Pradesh state.
   About 80,000 people have been arrested in the last week in the
rural state. Most were made under preventive detention laws that
allow authorities to hold people without charge when they believe
public safety is threatened.
   The detainees included top leaders of the right-wing Hindu
Bharatiya Janata Party. It has withdrawn its support for Prime
Minister Singh in Parliament, plunging India into political crisis.
   Singh now does not have a reliable vote bank in Parliament to
preserve his minority government, which took office last December.
   The mosque at issue was built on the place that many Hindu
leaders claim is the very spot where the god Rama was born.
   Moslems, who make up 12 percent of India's 880 million people,
fear that if one mosque is moved or destroyed, hundreds of other
Islamic shrines across India would be in peril.
   Athough India is constitutionally a secular nation, Hindus
comprise 82 percent of the population and have always held the
prime minister's post.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

