<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested about 1,000 Moslems
today when they tried to march to the nearby town of Ayodhya, where
triumphal Hindus celebrated the building of a new temple on a site
claimed by both religions.
   The Moslem protest was peaceful, but one of its leaders who was
arrested, Zafaryab Jilani, warned: ``When all these methods fail,
arms are taken up. The next generation may not listen to peaceful
protest.''
   At least 290 people have been killed in Hindu-Moslem violence in
three Indian states since August, when plans for the new temple
were announced. So far the violence has not spread to Ayodhya and
Faizabad, 330 miles southeast of the capital New Delhi.
   The demonstrators in Faizabad accused Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi and his Congress Party of caving in to Hindu fundamentalists
in a bid for votes from the Hindu majority in national elections
less than two weeks away.
