<HEAD>Moslems Protest, Hindus Celebrate Over Shrine Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FAIZABAD, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 1,000 Moslem protesters
Friday who tried to march to nearby Ayodhya, where celebrating
Hindus laid the foundation stone of a new temple at a site claimed
by both religions.
   The Moslem demonstration was peaceful, but Zafaryab Jilani, one
of its leaders, declared: ``When all these methods fail, arms are
taken up. The next generation may not listen to peaceful protest.''
   At least 290 people have been killed in Hindu-Moslem violence in
three Indian states since plans for the temple were announced in
August. No violence has been reported in Faizabad or Ayodhya.
   Protest leaders in Faizabad accused Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi
and his Congress Party of giving in to Hindu fundamentalists in a
quest for Hindu votes in national elections set for Nov. 22, 24 an
26.
   ``If this ruling Congress Party is ousted from power, perhaps
secular government can be saved,'' said Jilani, a senior leader of
the All-India Babri Masjid Action Committee.
   Babri Masjid, the Mosque of Babar, was built in the 17th century
on the spot in Ayodhya where Hindu fundamentalists claim one of
their most popular gods, Lord Ram, was born.
   About 90 minutes after the arrests in Faizabad, Hindus
celebrated the laying of the foundation stone of a new Ram temple
130 feet from the Babar Mosque. They flung marigold petals into a
6-foot-deep hole in which their leaders reverently placed bricks
and the stone.
   Police wearing helmets and chest protectors struggled to keep
from falling into the pit as at least 5,000 pilgrims pushed into
the small, hilltop enclave in less than an hour.
   The dispute over the Ayodhya hilltop in Uttar Pradesh state is
centuries old and the current chapter began on a night in 1949,
when a Ram idol was spirited into the mosque. A court ordered the
mosque closed to people of both faiths in an effort to prevent
religious strife.
   In 1986, another court order opened the Babar Mosque, but only
to Hindus. That decision prompted riots across India in which at
least 200 people died.
   Currently, the argument centers on who owns the land where the
foundation is being laid. Hindus and Moslems agree the small plot
intended for the stone is owned by a Hindu, but the rest of the
landed needed for the temple remains in dispute.
   Although Moslems opposed construction of the temple, they agreed
they could not prevent the stone from being laid in the plot owned
by a Hindu.
   Late Thursday night, however, Moslem activists contended the
foundation site was spilling over to property they claim is Moslem.
   Courts in Uttar Pradesh state, where Gandhi's Congress Party
controls the government, have declined to rule who owns the
property.
   ``After today, Moslems will not vote for Congress,'' Mohammad
Azam Khan, an Uttar Pradesh state legislator from the opposition
Janata Party, said Friday.
   Azam, like Jilani, is a convenor _ a sort of senior organizer _
of the Babri Masjid Action Committee. Both were among those
arrested in Faizabad.
   The arrests were part of a uniquely Indian form of peaceful
protest in which people do something they know police will not
allow, such as marching to Ayodhya, thus inviting arrest. The
police oblige by rounding them up, generally with little or no
force.
   In Faizabad, the Moslems and at least 40 Hindu sympathizers
climbed willingly into freight-hauling trucks and waved as they
were driven to a police compound on the outskirts.
   At the compound, they sat on the ground listening to leaders
exhort them to preserve India as a secular state and vote Gandhi
and his party out of office.
   Moslems, who make up 11 percent of India's 880 million people,
have given the Congress Party strong support since India's
independence from Britain in 1947. Gandhi faces a tough challenge
from Vishwanath Pratap Singh, leader of the National Front
coalition, and the Moslem vote could be pivotal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

