<HEAD>Hindu-Moslem Conflict: A Road Paved with Death, Bricks, Politics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swearing devotion to the Hindu god Ram
and a willingness to die for their beliefs, hundreds of young men
set out Saturday with sanctified bricks on a mission that has
spurred Hindu-Moslem riots and caused at least 280 deaths.
   Their destination is Ayodhya, 325 miles to the southeast, where
plans for a new Hindu temple have propelled religious strife to the
forefront of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's battle for re-election.
   From the width and depth of India, convoys of trucks and buses
are heading to Ayodhya in the heart of Uttar Pradesh, India's most
populous state and a bellwether in elections. In their wake,
Moslems and Hindus have shot, stabbed and burned each other to
death.
   ``To put up the bricks for the Hindus, this is important,'' said
Rajesh Kumar, a 19-year-old English student who joined the
procession of seven buses and at least four trucks that left New
Delhi on Saturday.
   ``The name of the god Ram is enough to defend ourselves,'' he
said, then patted a holster containing a brass trident with sharp
spears. ``The blade is less than 4 inches, so it's legally
permitted,'' he said with a grin. ``This is just a symbol, not a
weapon.''
   Some of the young men carried sabers and hockey sticks, which
older organizers hastened to describe as religious symbols or
evidence of youthful sportsmanship.
   On Thursday, ardent Hindus plan to lay the foundation for a new
temple to Lord Ram in Ayodhya next to a disputed shrine claimed by
both Moslems and Hindus.
   Vishwa Hindu Parishad, the fundamentalist group behind the
temple drive, says it has gathered bricks from more than 375,000
cities and towns throughout India and from Hindus in Canada, the
United States and Western Europe. After being blessed by Hindu holy
men, the bricks are borne by believers and festooned with bright
red and orange satin and chiffon, tied up with tinsel and garlanded
with marigolds.
   This joyous celebration of religious right has left a trail of
death in villages where Hindus and Moslems have lived side by side
for centuries.
   Hindu-Moslem clashes are particularly worrisome now.
   With national elections barely three weeks away, both Gandhi and
opposition leader Vishwanath Pratap Singh have been urging
religious harmony while at the same time trying not to alienate the
Hindu fundamentalist vote or the potentially pivotal vote of
Moslems, who make up 11 percent of the population. Hindus account
for 82 percent.
   Gandhi officially launched his campaign Friday in Faizabad, four
miles down the road from Ayodhya, with an accusation that unnamed
opposition parties were ``fanning communal feelings for their
vested political interests.''
   ``Communalism'' is the catchword Indian politicians and news
media use for religious strife in an effort to avoid singling out
specific faiths or being perceived as taking sides.
   Back in New Delhi, Singh of the opposition National Front
coalition was accusing Gandhi's Congress Party of trying to turn
Ayodhya into ``a flashpoint'' of communal violence.
   Many participants in Saturday's send-off of the convoy said they
would vote for the Bharatiya Janata Party. This right-wing Hindu
party is not a member of the National Front but has been making
deals with the front for a share of the Parliament seats to be
determined in the elections being conducted Nov. 22, 24 and 26.
   The young men making the trip, as well as older ones encouraging
them, vowed that the journey would be peaceful unless ``the
Mohammedans'' started something or the government failed to
maintain order.
   In late October, similar ``Ram shila,'' or Ram brick,
processions precipitated several days of Hindu-Moslem clashes in
Bihar state. At least 201 people died by official count, which does
not specify the victims' religions.
   Indian newspapers have given indications that many, perhaps
most, of the victims were Moslems. When the dead and wounded have
been identified, the names have usually been Islamic.
   In addition to the October deaths, about 80 other people have
been killed in Bihar and four other states since August when plans
were announced to build the temple at Ayodhya, revered by Hindus as
Ram's birthplace.
   The New Delhi convoy of trucks and buses, with their load of
5,045 bricks and about 300 men, is to pass through towns with
sizeable Moslem populations.
   ``What can we say about trouble?'' asked R.K. Mathur, a
40-year-old music teacher attired in blue denim jeans and jacket.
``We are going on our mission.''
   Manesh Gupta, a 19-year-old photographer, added: ``If we die, it
is no problem _ 100 percent, no problem.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>

