<HEAD>Indian Leader Seeks Peaceful End to Battle Over Religious Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIJAY JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister V.P. Singh on Monday
appealed for a peaceful resolution to a religious site dispute that
has caused violent Hindu-Moslem clashes and could threaten the
Singh's coalition government.
   ``Religious fanaticism is the first step towards the foundation
for a theocratic state. It will be the death of India as a secular
state,'' Singh said during a 20-minute televised speech.
   At least 80 people have died this year in battles over a 16th
century mosque, the Babri Masjid, in Ayodhya, about 310 miles east
of New Delhi.
   Hindus believe the town was the birthplace of a god, Rama, and
want to dismantle the mosque, claiming it was built by Mogul rulers
on the foundations of an ancient Hindu temple.
   The Hindu World Council has vowed to start rebuilding the temple
Oct. 30, but a Moslem group had said it will protect the mosque.
Hindus comprise 82 percent of India's 880 million people. Moslems
account for 12 percent.
   Singh said he has appointed five state chief ministers to help
``solve the issue.'' Chief ministers are the highest elected
officials of a state.
   He also asked the Hindu fundamentalist Bharatiya Janata Party to
work toward a nonviolent solution.
   There was no immediate reaction from the Bharatiya Janata, or
Indian People's Party. Several other political parties and groups
have unsuccessfully appealed to the party to call off its campaign.
   Singh's 10-month-old National Front coalition government needs
the Bharatiya Janata Party and the Left Front, a conglomeration of
communist groups, to remain intact.
   The Bharatiya Janata Party has threatened to withdraw support
from the government if the proposed temple construction is
disrupted.
   ``How can a country be governed in circumstances like this? Is
it necessary that the country has to be plunged into communal
chaos? Can't they wait to build the temple until a peaceful
settlement has been reached?'' asked Singh, whose Janata Dal party
comprises the largest part of the coalition government.
   ``Hundreds of governments can come and go but the nation should
remain one,'' he said. ``Government is too small a consideration
when people are involved.''
   Clashes between the Moslems and Hindus escalated last month
after Bharatiya Janata Party leader Lal Krishna Advani set off on a
6,000-mile van journey from a west Indian Hindu shrine to Ayodhya.
   Advani is scheduled to reach Ayodhya on Oct. 30. Authorities in
Uttar Pradesh state have said they may arrest Advani when he
crosses the state border.
   Fearing unrest, police already have detained more than 20,000
Hindu activists. Many road and rail links to Ayodhya have been
blocked or subject to stringent checks.
</TEXT>
