<BYLINE>By VIJAY JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AYODHYA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police killed at least 12 Hindus
attempting to storm a disputed Moslem mosque Friday, and more than
40 others died in violence as the religious dispute spread across
India to neighboring Moslem countries.
   Ten consecutive days of clashes between majority Hindus and
minority Moslems have left nearly 280 dead in India and at least
three dead in predominately Islamic Bangladesh.
   The unrest could also weaken Prime Minister V.P. Singh's chances
of surviving a Nov. 7 confidence vote. Singh lost his majority in
Parliament after Hindus withdrew from the 11-month-old coalition to
protest government handling of the mosque dispute.
   Fundamentalist Hindus seek to destroy the hilltop Babri Mosque
and build a a Hindu temple on the site in Ayodhya, 300 miles
southeast of New Delhi.
   Hindus say the 460-year-old mosque was built on the foundation
of an early temple marking the birthplace of Rama, the
much-worshiped warrior god. Moslems dispute the history and say
relinquishing the mosque would jeopardize hundreds of other Moslem
sites.
   Police have fired twice this week on Hindus attempting to
overrun the mosque. On Friday, a top district official said
witnesses' estimate of 12 dead was ``nearer to the truth'' than
reporters' tally of 10. The official spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Doctors at a hospital in the nearby town of Faizabad said they
treated 64 injured people, including 48 wounded by gunfire. Several
policemen were also treated, they said.
   Reporters saw three buses and several jeeps torched by the mob.
Some homes were also burned.
   At least 25 deaths were reported in related riots across the
Uttar Pradesh state, where the mosque is located, the Press Trust
of India news agency reported.
   Thirteen more died Friday in the western state of Gujarat, the
news agency said. Other deaths were reported from Karnataka, Bihar,
Rajasthan and Andhra Pradesh states.
   At least 279 people have died in India in recent violence linked
to the dispute, police and news agencies report. Last year, about
900 people were killed when a Hindu group first announced its
intention to take over the site by force.
   Most of those killed near the mosque recently were Hindus, but
authorities refuse to identify the faith of other victims out of
fear of exacerbating tensions.
   In Bangladesh, which has a Hindu minority, two people died
Friday of bullet wounds suffered during anti-Hindu protest earlier
this week in the capital of Dhaka.
   At least three people have been killed and 350 wounded in three
days of rioting in Dhaka and in 12 other cities. Two of those
killed were Moslems, and the religion of the third victim was not
immediately known.
   In Pakistan, India's predominately Islamic western neighbor,
several demonstrations were held to protest the violence and some
Islamic leaders called for larger pro-Moslem rallies.
   Pakistan's caretaker prime minister, Ghulam Mustafa Jatoi, said
the Indian government was half-heartedly protecting Moslem shrines.
   ``It was the moral duty of the Indian government to protect the
places of worship of Moslems,'' Jatoi said in a statemenet
published in the Pakistan Times. ``India, which pleads herself the
champion of secularism, has failed to give protection to holy
places of Moslems.''
   But one of those injured Friday near the mosque accused
government forces of shooting needlessly.
   ``Two policemen dragged a man out of the house and shot him in
the chest. Then they also shot two people who were crying over a
dead body. They were shot in the back,''said Bhupendra Singh
Rawat, speaking from a hospital bed.
   Rawat, a 24-year-old insurance agent from New Delhi, said he was
knocked down by a police officer's bamboo club.
   Former Indian Deputy Prime Minister Devi Lal, a key figure in
efforts to replace Singh, said a government comprising all parties
should be set up to defuse the crisis.
   Singh, who lost his majority in Parliament after the pro-Hindu
Bharatiya Janata Party withdrew, is expected to lose the
no-confidence vote. The prime minister is also beset by moves
within his National Front coalition for a new leader.
   Some newspapers and political commentators have called the
Ayodhya dispute the greatest threat to the country's secularism
since India gained independence in 1947.
   India's 880 million people are 82 percent Hindu and 12 percent
Moslem. The others include Sikhs, Christians and Buddhists. India's
constitution pledges tolerance of all religions and secularism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

