<HEADLINE>  HINDU PILGRIMS FLOCK TO HOLY SITE AFTER DISPUTED
SHRINE REOPENS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The temple, now housed in a 16th-century mosque on a small hill, is
believed by Rama's followers to be his birthplace.;    The site is the center
of a bitter dispute between Hindus and Muslims that led to rioting in India
last year as Hindu fundamentalists demanded that the mosque be torn down and
replaced with a larger temple.;    The campaign helped topple the minority
government of Prime Minister V.P. Singh and will be a factor in the general
elections in May. The Muslims say there is no basis for the Hindu belief that
a temple existed at the site before the mosque.;    Negotiations to settle the
issue have stalled, although the tensions of last November have abated. In
last year's violence, more than 100 people were reportedly killed when they
defied a ban on marches.;    Tight security measures were enforced in the last
week, the first time that the shrine had been opened to the public in such
large numbers since last October.;    Hundreds of armed troops around the
small, white-washed building searched the pilgrims with metal detectors and
constructed 8- to 10-foot-high barricades of iron pipes topped with barbed
wire.;    Police kept watch through hidden cameras and viewed closed-circuit
television monitors during part of the celebrations.;    The Hindu faith is
embraced by more than 600 million of India's population of 843 million. The
right-wing, nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, with its espousal of the
temple at Ayodhya, 300 miles southeast of New Delhi, is seeking to convert
