<HEAD>Death Toll Reaches 89 in Hindu-Moslem Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The religious dispute that pits Hindus
against Moslems is threatening to bring down the government, and
the death toll in the violence has risen to 89, according to news
reports today.
   United News of India reported that 71 people died Wednesday and
Thursday in religious riots in the cities of Jaipur and Jodhpur in
western Rajasthan state.
   The news agency quoted hospital sources as saying 68 bodies of
people killed in the rioting had been brought to Jaipur, and at
least three other people were known to have died.
   Elsewhere in the country, news reports said that at least 18
others had died in Hindu-Moslem clashes since Tuesday when the
leader of a right-wing Hindu party was arrested.
   Lal Krishna Advani was detained while leading a caravan across
northern Indian to rally support for a campaign to replace a 16th
century Moslem mosque with a Hindu temple in the Uttar Pradesh city
of Ayodhya. Hindus claim the mosque, built in 1528, is on the site
of the birthplace of Lord Rama, and thus is as holy to Hindus as
Mecca is to Moslems.
   The arrest of Advani, president of the Bharatiya Janata Party,
triggered riots in a half-dozen states where large Moslem
communities are mingled among the Hindu majority.
   As many as 50,000 supporters of Advani's party have been placed
under ``preventive arrest'' over the past two weeks. Indian law
allows people to be detained without charges when authorities fear
there is a threat to public safety.
   After Advani's arrest, his party withdrew its support for
Singh's coalition government, plunging India into a political
crisis. The party's defection deprived Singh of a parliamentary
majority.
   Singh said he would seek a vote of confidence on Nov. 7 to prove
he could still muster a parliamentary majority.
   But the Congress Party, the largest opposition party, said it
would oppose Singh in any vote of confidence because of his
handling of the religious dispute.
   Within Singh's fractious Janata Dal party, there appeared to be
moves under way to oust him as party leader.
   The Times of India newspaper reported a concerted effort in top
party circles to replace Singh so Janata Dal could remain in power.
   The national daily said smaller parties in the government
coalition had indicated they ``would not be adverse to support a
government minus V.P. Singh ... if it can spare the nation travails
of another parliamentary poll within a year.''
   Singh's Janata Dal party and smaller partners in his National
Front coalition government now hold 146 seats in the 522-member
policy-making lower house - the Lok Sabha, or House of the People.
   He still has the support of the Communist-led Left Front
alliance, which has 51 seats, but the loss of the 86 seats held by
the Bharatiya Janata Party has cost him his majority.
   The opposition Congress Party and its allies hold 210 seats. The
remainder are held by smaller parties and independents.
   The political crisis was triggered by a religious dispute over a
shrine in Ayodhya, a town of 40,000 in Uttar Pradesh.
   Tens of thousands of Hindus have converged on Ayodhya this week
to help build the temple. The government has dispatched tens of
thousands of police and paramilitary troops to prevent violent
clashes.
   Singh and his Janata Dal party allies who run Uttar Pradesh's
state government have tried to halt construction of the temple
until a court can rule on the religious dispute.
   Moslems comprise only 12 percent of India's 880 million people.
India is officially a secular state, but the Hindus make up 82
percent of the population and dominate the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

