<BYLINE>By VIJAY JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AYODHYA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Special trains carried people from
riot-torn areas near a disputed mosque Saturday as fundamentalist
Hindus debated whether to keep up efforts to seize the site.
   At least 305 deaths have been reported across India in unrest
linked to attempts by Hindus to raze the 16th century mosque and
build a Hindu temple in Ayodhya, about 300 miles southeast of New
Delhi.
   At least 13 people died Saturday in areas around Ayodhya,
including a police constable who had suffered head wounds during
Hindu attempts to storm the mosque Friday.
   Police, meanwhile, arrested a newspaper editor and blocked
distribution of 10 Hindi-language newspapers for allegedly
misreporting the distrubances that have raged since Oct. 24.
   The editor of the weekly newspaper Swatantra Chetna was arrested
on charges of inciting communal violence through exaggerated
reporting, and officials in the city of Varanasi filed court cases
against several dailies, the United News of India agency reported
Saturday.
   All the newspapers are published in Uttar Pradesh state, the
center of the religious conflict. The agency said 200 journalists
who protested the police action in Varanasi were briefly arrested.
   Police with shoot-on-sight orders patrolled five northern Indian
towns under curfew, but did not interfere with people heading
toward the bus and train stations in Ayodhya.
   All rail service to the area was halted last week as part of the
government's effort to keep temple activists from reaching Ayodhya.
Three special trains were dispatched to the town Saturday.
   The sectarian violence has brought Prime Minister V.P. Singh's
11-month-old coalition government to the brink of collapse. Singh,
who faces a confidence vote Wednesday, lost his majority in
Parliament when a right-wing Hindu party withdrew support because
of the Ayodhya dispute.
   In Ayodhya, Hindu leaders debated whether to continue attempts
to take control of the 460-year-old mosque, which they claim was
built on the foundation of an early temple marking the birthplace
of the god Rama.
   Moslems dispute the history and say relinquishing the mosque
would jeopardize hundreds of other Moslem sites.
   Leaders of the World Hindu Council, the group leading the
temple-building project, are split over the best tactic to pursue
next.
   Nritya Gopal Das, an Ayodhya priest and a local leader of the
council, has been asking people to leave town, saying they had
achieved victory Tuesday when they stormed the mosque and pried a
few bricks from its walls and chipped concrete from the domed roof.
   But a national leader of the council, general secretary Ashok
Singhal, has been urging people to stay until the temple is
constructed.
   Hindus make up 82 percent of India's 880 million people, while
Moslems comprise 12 percent.
   In Bangladesh, authorities relaxed curfews in the capital of
Dhaka and Chittagong for 10 hours Saturday after several days of
anti-Hindu riots across the predominately Moslem nation.
   At least four people have died and more than 400 were injured in
the violence that started Tuesday in Bangladesh.
</TEXT>
