<HEAD>Singh Holds Rally to Contain Rebellion in His Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister V.P. Singh called his
supporters to a rally Saturday as he attempted to contain a
rebellion by party members who want him to resign.
   In a speech to 2,000 loyalists on the lawn of his home, Singh
gave no indication he was ready to step down. He pledged his Janata
Dal party would champion the downtrodden, as he said it had done
since he took office in December.
   Environment Minister Maneka Gandhi quit Singh's Cabinet on
Friday, accusing the prime minister of failing to keep his pledge
of honesty and efficiency. Four Parliament members once considered
close to Singh called on him to step down.
   Singh faces a no-confidence motion in a special session of the
legislature Nov. 7. Barring a last-minute compromise or a political
realignment, he seems certain to lose.
   Singh has been in trouble since Tuesday, when a Hindu-Moslem
dispute over rights to a holy site ballooned into the worst
political crisis of the 10-month-old government.
   He was elected largely on the votes of the middle and educated
classes who were disenchanted with the Congress government led by
Rajiv Gandhi.
   As prime minister, Singh adopted policies aimed at expanding
support with the poor, alienating many of those who put him in
power.
   He also opposed construction of a Hindu temple at Ayodhya, where
a Moslem mosque stands. That alienated the right-wing Bharatiya
Janata Party, and without its support Singh's coalition no longer
has a majority in Parliament.
   At least 93 people died last week in rioting between Moslems and
Hindus and police efforts to quell the disturbances.
   Police on Friday night clamped a curfew on Ayodhya and on the
neighboring town of Faizabad.
   Hindu fundamentalists have vowed to build a temple at the site
which they say is birthplace of Lord Rama, a Hindu god. However,
the mosque has stood there for 460 years.
   Police said they have detained 51,000 people in Uttar Pradesh
state and seized more than 35,000 tribal spears and other weapons
from Hindus on their way to Ayodhya, 300 miles southeast of New
Delhi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

